text-unit.text:
To begin, fill in the fields to be completed at top of the asmejour-template.tex file. The first are pdf metadata in the preamble that will tag the pdf file itself. Next is the
\JourName{..}
command, which should be changed as appropriate (omit “Journal of”).

The title should be placed into 

 \title{..}

, and line breaks may be specified if desired. Keywords may optionally be in
cluding using the 

 \keywords{..}

 command; this command 

 must 

be issued before the abstract. To omit keywords, just omit this command. Next, the abstract text must be placed into 

 \begin{abstract}

…

 \end{abstract}

. The abstract will auto
matically be italicized.

 The vertical bar in the 
title block is black in all ASME journals. Since the asmejour class is only for preprints, we include the [fun] option to have the bar in color. Any color name recognized by the xcolor package [



  1



] may be invoked by including the option [barcolor=name] in the 

 \documentclass[..]{asmejour}

 command. The color for this example is Goldenrod3. To have a black bar, either omit barcolor entirely or use the name black.

Citations will be numbered automatically [
2
]. They should be inserted at the appropriate point using a
\cite{ref}
com mand [
3
,
4
]. The citations will be automatically sorted and com pressed, as well, if they are given in a set [
2
,
5
–
10
]. If naming a reference explicitly, put “Ref.” in front of the number, as in Ref. [
9
]. Reference [
9
] is appropriate at the beginning of a sentence. See the asmeconf-sample.bib file for examples of how to enter your references.

ASME sets section headings and captions in bold face. In ad
dition, the captions are in sans-serif type. The asmejour class chose appropriate fonts automatically. You can place 

 \cite{..}

, 

 \ref{..}

, 

 \label{..}

, and into headings and captions directly, as you would in the main text. You can place 

 \footnote{..}

 into headings, but not into captions.





   2









   2





   See tex-stackexchange for various approaches to footnotes in captions, if they seem necessary. For footnotes in tables, use the tablefootnote package.

If you wish to override the default math format in a heading or caption, put 

 \mathversion{normal}

 in the heading or caption.

Landscape figures and tables may be produced at full-page size by putting 

 \usepackage[figuresright]{rotating}

 in your .tex file’s preamble and using the sidewaystable* and sidewaysfigure* environments [



  13



].

 When the en

tries 

 @article{..

, 

 @book{..

, 

 @inbook{..

, 

 @incollection{..

, 

 @proceedings{..

, or 

 @techreport{..

 include 

 doi={..}

, the document title, paper number, or report number will be hyper
linked to that doi number, and the doi number will not be printed. If no doi is included, but a url or eprint is included, then the title will be hyperlinked to that url or eprint. To display the doi (or the url or eprint when no doi is given), put it into the 

 note={..}

 field (using 

 \doi{..}

 or 

 \url{..}

 ) like this:

 The 

 urldate={..}

 field may be used to 
provide the date on which a given url was accessed. By default, the text printed will be accessed `date',. The word “accessed” may be changed using the 

 urltype={..}

 field.

 For the entry types 

 @inproceeedings{..

 and 

 @proceeedings{..

, you may include 

 venue={..}

 and 

 eventdate={..}

 to specify the city and the date of a conference. Omit 

 address={..}

 if 

 venue={..}

 is used.

 The 

 version={..}

 field may be used 
with 

 @book

, 

 @online

, and 

 @manual

. By default, the text will read Version `number' as in Refs. [



  15



,



  16



], but different wording may be selected using the 

 versiontype={..}

 field, e.g., to say “Revision” or something similar, as in Ref. [



  17



]. ASME often puts the version in the title, as in Refs. [



  18



,



  19



], so I’ve left the final decision for discussion between the authors and the copy editor.

 In addition to the standard entry, 

 @incollection{..

, an entry 

 @inserialcollection{..

 is de
fined for serials in which each volume has a different title. See the asmejour-sample.bib file for discussion and compare Ref. [



  20



] to Ref. [



  21



].

In most cases, long equations can be kept below the column width by using one of the multiline equation environments de fined by amsmath, such as align, split, or multline [
22
]. The following equation is set with the multline environment:

